The paper deals with machine learning tasks and the design of mechanisms for online procurement of data held by strategic agents. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the study of a model in which agents may lie about their cost of furnishing their data, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of past data to actively price future data, which suggests that it may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of algorithms and analysis, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves a budget constraint and the use of no-regret learning, which suggests that it may also belong to the Economics and Computation (cs.EC) sub-category.
